1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:00,962
TL;DR.

2
00:00:00,962 --> 00:00:03,087
This week in 30 seconds:.

3
00:00:03,087 --> 00:00:13,400
GPT-5.6 Launch: US government intervenes preventively for the first time — only ~20 pre-approved partners receive access instead of everyone.

4
00:00:13,400 --> 00:00:22,450
Anthropic comeback: Mythos-5 export ban lifts after 14 days — 100+ US agencies and companies are unlocked again.

5
00:00:22,450 --> 00:00:34,475
Vacuum effect: Japanese (Sakana AI) and Chinese startups (Zhipu AI) launch frontier models — the export ban accelerates exactly the competition it aims to prevent.

6
00:00:34,475 --> 00:00:45,375
Content deal: Getty stock jumps +145% intraday after ChatGPT partnership — fair image licensing in AI systems becomes a business model.

7
00:00:45,375 --> 00:00:46,625
Story of the Week.

8
00:00:46,625 --> 00:00:52,700
Historic First: US Government Stops GPT-5.6 — Before It Launches.

9
00:00:52,700 --> 00:01:00,475
For the first time in US history, a government has actively restricted the release of a commercial AI model — before its launch .

10
00:01:00,475 --> 00:01:10,525
The Office of the National Cyber Director and the OSTP asked OpenAI to release GPT-5.6 only to a small group of pre-approved partners .

11
00:01:10,525 --> 00:01:11,925
Not after an incident.

12
00:01:11,925 --> 00:01:13,425
Not after a disaster.

13
00:01:13,425 --> 00:01:14,450
Preemptively.

14
00:01:14,450 --> 00:01:35,000
GPT-5.6 comprises three models: Sol (flagship, $5 / 1M input tokens, $30 / 1M output tokens), Terra (balanced, half the price of Sol), and Luna (fast and affordable, $1 / 1M input, $6 / 1M output) .

15
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:43,037
Only around 20 companies receive access for now — each additional unlock must be individually approved by US agencies .

16
00:01:43,037 --> 00:01:47,925
"We don't believe this kind of government access process should become the long-term default.

17
00:01:47,925 --> 00:01:55,375
It keeps the best tools from users, developers, enterprises, cyber defenders, and global partners who need them."

18
00:01:55,375 --> 00:01:56,300
— OpenAI

19
00:01:56,300 --> 00:02:04,125
The precedent that triggered this process is the complete export ban on Anthropic's Fable 5, which took effect on June 12 .

20
00:02:04,125 --> 00:02:13,462
The White House has since been working on a framework for safety evaluation of new frontier models and requires voluntary reviews 30 days before release .

21
00:02:13,462 --> 00:02:15,287
Why is the government intervening?

22
00:02:15,287 --> 00:02:29,750
Officially the focus is on national security and dual-use risks: frontier models with strong coding capabilities could be used for cyberattacks, bioweapon development, or by state adversaries — according to the security agencies' rationale.

23
00:02:29,750 --> 00:02:34,475
The framework aims to ensure risk assessments happen before launch rather than after.

24
00:02:34,475 --> 00:02:52,887
Dean Ball, former White House AI advisor and future OpenAI employee, warns from a libertarian policy perspective — and thus as a party with a clear vested interest — that Trump's Executive Order establishes a de-facto licensing requirement for frontier AI that could lead to systematic delays .

25
00:02:52,887 --> 00:03:01,212
For developers and businesses this means: Frontier AI access is no longer a right but a governmentally controllable privilege.

26
00:03:01,212 --> 00:03:10,337
Anyone building on OpenAI or Anthropic today must now factor in not only pricing risks — but availability risks from government decisions.

27
00:03:10,337 --> 00:03:14,662
Multi-provider strategies are no longer a precaution but a necessity.

28
00:03:14,662 --> 00:03:26,187
Critical voices: Observers question whether preventive controls without a clear legal basis are constitutionally viable and whether the process is transparent enough for the affected companies.

29
00:03:26,187 --> 00:03:33,362
OpenAI itself is cooperating — but explicitly emphasizes that this must not become a permanent state of affairs .

30
00:03:33,362 --> 00:03:45,100
Bottom line: The US government has fired the starting gun: anyone developing frontier AI will need government approval going forward — and OpenAI played along for the first time without blocking.

31
00:03:45,100 --> 00:03:46,437
More Top Stories.

32
00:03:46,437 --> 00:03:52,075
Export Ban Reversal: Anthropic's Mythos 5 Returns — for the Select Few.

33
00:03:52,075 --> 00:04:02,625
Fourteen days after the complete export ban on Anthropic's Fable 5 / Mythos 5, Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick lifts the restrictions partially via letter .

34
00:04:02,625 --> 00:04:12,112
More than 100 US government agencies and critical infrastructure companies regain access — including for non-American employees of those organizations .

35
00:04:12,112 --> 00:04:19,937
"I have determined that appropriate safeguards are in place to permit certain trusted partners to access the Claude Mythos 5 Model."

36
00:04:19,937 --> 00:04:22,375
— Howard Lutnick, Commerce Secretary

37
00:04:22,490 --> 00:04:29,065
The complete export ban for the general public and international users, however, remains in place.

38
00:04:29,065 --> 00:04:41,515
Anthropic, with an ARR of $47 billion in May 2026 (according to industry reports, not independently verified), had been negotiating with the US government since June 12 .

39
00:04:41,515 --> 00:04:52,540
The model was simply unavailable to 99% of users for fourteen days — a substantial economic damage that brutally exposes the dependency on government decisions.

40
00:04:52,540 --> 00:05:00,227
The pattern becomes clear: government access first, general public later (maybe) — and international partners at the very back.

41
00:05:00,227 --> 00:05:05,090
The Vacuum Paradox: Export Bans Breed the Competition They're Meant to Fight.

42
00:05:05,090 --> 00:05:12,252
While Fable 5 remains blocked for international users, Japanese and Chinese startups are launching competing models .

43
00:05:12,252 --> 00:05:22,715
Sakana AI from Tokyo presents "Fugu" — positioned as on par with "Fable 5 and Mythos Preview," optimized for agent orchestration and Japanese .

44
00:05:22,715 --> 00:05:36,327
Sakana, valued at $2.65 billion (according to company statements, Series B, November 2025) with $135 million in funding, is no longer a garage startup .

45
00:05:36,327 --> 00:05:39,277
"Access to top models can disappear overnight."

46
00:05:39,277 --> 00:05:41,465
— David Ha, Sakana CEO

47
00:05:41,465 --> 00:05:52,640
In parallel, Zhipu AI (Tsinghua spinout) from China brings the models "Tulongfeng" and "Yitianzhen" — specialized in cybersecurity and vulnerability detection .

48
00:05:52,640 --> 00:06:03,815
The irony is hard to miss: US export bans, designed to secure technological leadership, are accelerating exactly the international development of frontier alternatives .

49
00:06:03,815 --> 00:06:18,365
An important distinction: Japanese alternatives like Sakana AI are considered geopolitically unproblematic for Western allies — Chinese cybersecurity models like those from Zhipu AI are a different category from a US security perspective.

50
00:06:18,365 --> 00:06:22,965
The export ban treats both equally, but creates very different risks.

51
00:06:22,965 --> 00:06:30,940
Sakana co-founder Ren Ito puts it plainly: "The first priority should be preserving access for America's closest allies." .

52
00:06:30,940 --> 00:06:36,852
Getty + OpenAI: The First Major Precedent for Fair Content Compensation in AI.

53
00:06:36,852 --> 00:06:41,677
Getty Images and OpenAI are entering a multi-year display partnership .

54
00:06:41,677 --> 00:06:52,702
When ChatGPT can illustrate a response with a real image, a licensed Getty photo appears — with attribution, without training use, with indemnification for Getty customers .

55
00:06:52,702 --> 00:07:04,365
Around 600,000 content creators and 360 content partners are affected, with coverage spanning 160,000+ events per year according to Getty .

56
00:07:04,365 --> 00:07:09,577
"High-quality, licensed visual content makes AI-powered search more trustworthy."

57
00:07:09,577 --> 00:07:12,427
— Craig Peters, CEO Getty Images

58
00:07:12,427 --> 00:07:16,702
Caveat: The model applies only to Getty-represented creators.

59
00:07:16,702 --> 00:07:26,727
The majority of photographers worldwide — who don't license through Getty — receive no compensation and no attribution when their images end up in AI training data.

60
00:07:26,727 --> 00:07:35,927
The market responded decisively: an intraday price surge of up to 145%, closing price approximately +90% .

61
00:07:35,927 --> 00:07:43,452
This is no coincidence — it's a signal that investors take fair licensing seriously as a scalable AI business model.

62
00:07:43,452 --> 00:07:53,452
For the entire content industry — music, text, video — this is a precedent: not bans or lawsuits, but partnership models could be the way forward.

63
00:07:53,452 --> 00:07:54,402
Quick Hits.

64
00:07:54,402 --> 00:07:55,477
Briefly noted:.

65
00:07:55,477 --> 00:08:15,115
Claude vs. ChatGPT: ChatGPT's market share among paying users fell below 50% for the first time (46.4%); Gemini holds 27.7%, Claude 10.3% — among premium users, Claude scores disproportionately through coding strength and quality .

66
00:08:15,115 --> 00:08:29,302
Adobe + Topaz: Adobe acquires Topaz Labs, known for AI-based image and video upscaling and noise reduction — a direct attack on generative AI competition in the creative market via the Firefly ecosystem .

67
00:08:29,302 --> 00:08:45,552
AI Energy Shift: Former Databricks AI chief founds startup with a promise: 1,000x reduction in AI energy consumption through novel hardware architecture — concrete details are still pending, but the political nerve has been struck .

68
00:08:45,552 --> 00:08:46,677
Tool of the Week.

69
00:08:46,677 --> 00:08:51,665
HuggingFace Jobs — Private vLLM Inference Server with a Single Command.

70
00:08:51,665 --> 00:09:03,340
HuggingFace enables launching a private, OpenAI-compatible LLM inference endpoint on HF infrastructure — no own GPU, no Kubernetes, no idle costs .

71
00:09:03,340 --> 00:09:05,665
A single command is all it takes:.

72
00:09:05,786 --> 00:09:13,223
hf jobs run --flavor a10g-large --expose 8000 --timeout 2h \

73
00:09:13,223 --> 00:09:17,086
vllm/vllm-openai:latest \

74
00:09:17,086 --> 00:09:24,761
vllm serve Qwen/Qwen3-4B --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000

75
00:09:24,761 --> 00:09:39,448
Pay-per-second billing, various GPU flavors (A10G, etc.), authentication via HF token out-of-the-box, and support for large models via tensor parallelism (e.g. Qwen3.5-122B) .

76
00:09:39,448 --> 00:09:53,786
The feature is a practical counterpoint to the closed-source chip strategies of OpenAI and Google: anyone who needs open-source models with high-performance inference without wanting to operate their own infrastructure gets a ready-to-deploy solution here.

77
00:09:53,786 --> 00:09:56,923
HuggingFace vLLM Jobs Documentation

78
00:09:56,923 --> 00:09:58,073
Fail of the Week.

79
00:09:58,073 --> 00:10:04,686
"Orbital AI Data Centers by 2028" — when even SoftBank's Masayoshi Son hits the brakes

80
00:10:04,686 --> 00:10:16,898
SoftBank CEO Masayoshi Son — known for billion-dollar bets on wild ideas like WeWork and Uber — publicly questions the feasibility of Elon Musk's plans for orbital AI data centers .

81
00:10:16,898 --> 00:10:19,561
Sam Altman also expresses skepticism.

82
00:10:19,561 --> 00:10:24,811
When the man who invented the "Vision Fund" pumps the brakes, a second look is warranted.

83
00:10:24,811 --> 00:10:34,373
Root cause: The next two to three years are decisive in the AI race — and orbital-based solutions simply don't help with the acute infrastructure bottleneck.

84
00:10:34,373 --> 00:10:41,723
There's also a structural problem: more orbital data centers means more SpaceX launches, means more revenue for Musk.

85
00:10:41,723 --> 00:10:46,273
When the seller promotes the product, in English that's called "Talking Your Book" .

86
00:10:46,273 --> 00:10:52,348
What we learn: Infrastructure hype is dangerous when timelines and feasibility remain unclear.

87
00:10:52,348 --> 00:11:01,711
When evaluating any bold infrastructure vision, ask first: who benefits from the hype — and are the assumptions physically and economically sound?

88
00:11:01,711 --> 00:11:02,848
Number of the Week.

89
00:11:02,848 --> 00:11:05,136
+145%

90
00:11:05,136 --> 00:11:16,286
That's how much the Getty Images stock rose intraday on June 21 after the display partnership with OpenAI was announced (closing price: approximately +90%) .

91
00:11:16,286 --> 00:11:30,748
This is the largest single-day gain by an established media and content company following an AI partnership — and a clear market signal that licensing models are taken seriously as a sustainable bridge between the content industry and AI.

92
00:11:30,748 --> 00:11:41,048
The signal is unambiguous: the market believes not only that AI and content can coexist — it believes that licensing models will revalue the content industry.

93
00:11:41,048 --> 00:11:50,473
For everyone who creates and licenses content, this is a strong sign that fair partnership with AI companies is economic value, not capitulation.

